I had an AAA bypass. My BP is running too high. The aortic aneurysm around the stent has reached 8.4 cm. A PSVT could have fatal consequences; bursting the aorta. If an episode occurs, ablation may become needed.

I had undergone testing to check the size of the aortic sac surrounding the AAA bypass stent. It had again increased to 8.6 cm x 8.2 cm with no apparent leak(s). My vascular surgeon is quite concerned because of the continued increase and the size it is now. He gave me a choice: Let it continue untreated, or, have surgery to either correct the unfound leak or have the aorta replaced with a tube in the affected area. The latter is quite major surgery. I chose that as the alternative is waiting for it to burst from a number of different causes including an episode of my PSVT or someone unknowingly performing a Heimlich maneuver.

Since 7/24/2019, I have spent 20 days in hospitals. I had an AAA bypass repair to stop an unexplained leak in the stent placed in my aorta three years ago. This required 33 staples from the abdomen to solar plexus. Within just over a week, my blood pressure went too high for just having this surgery and I was sent to a local ER for monitoring. Two days later I doubled over in extreme pain and was given a CT scan with contrast that revealed an endoleak. I was sent to the first hospital for further treatment that included another surgery to do a better repair. The reason I was given was that the combination of high BP plus my PSVT caused the stent to allow seepage resulting in problems with the stent. The manufacturer's rep worked with my surgeon to correct this.
Since my AAA surgery, I try to avoid situations that could cause endoleakage at the stent in my aorta.
